    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nIt is possible to swap out the buffer in a window opened by `vim.lsp.util.open_floating_preview()`.\n\nThis function is used by e.g. `vim.diagnostic.open_float()` and `vim.lsp.buf.hover()`. The content in these windows can be rather short. Being able to switch out the buffer in what is a preview window (you're not able to edit diagnostics in the float, neither can you edit the content of `vim.lsp.buf.hover()`) does not feel intuitive. \n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nVersion with a focused floating window:\n\nnvim --clean\n:lua namespace_index = vim.api.nvim_create_namespace(\"Test\")\n:lua vim.diagnostic.set(namespace_index, vim.fn.bufnr(), {{lnum=0,col=0,message=\"Test\"}})\n:lua vim.diagnostic.open_float()\n:lua vim.diagnostic.open_float()\n:e test\n\nVersion without focusing the floating window: \n\n:lua namespace_index = vim.api.nvim_create_namespace(\"Test\")\n:lua vim.diagnostic.set(namespace_index, vim.fn.bufnr(), {{lnum=0,col=0,message=\"Test\"}})\n:lua bufnr, winid = vim.diagnostic.open_float()\n:lua vim.api.nvim_win_set_buf(winid, vim.fn.bufnr())\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nYou should not be able to switch out buffers in windows opened by `vim.lsp.util.open_floating_preview()`.\n\nI have two candidate solutions for this in mind:\n\n1. The easiest would probably be to set the `winfixbuf` option for the window created by `vim.lsp.util.open_floating_preview()`. \n2. Check if there is a floating window opened by `vim.lsp.util.open_floating_preview()`, return to the previous window and then open the new buffer. I'm not sure if this is something that's realistically implementable. Feel like this has a lot of potential implementation efforts without bringing a lot of value. However, I still think this would be a nice approach.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.12.1\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNo\n\n### Operating system/version\n\n6.6.87.2-microsoft-standard-WSL2 (Ubuntu 24.04.4 LTS)\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nWindows Terminal 1.23.20211.0\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\ntmux-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nbob-nvim (neovim version manager)",
